WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.839 --> 00:00:07.839
(<i> phone rings</i>)

2
00:00:12.246 --> 00:00:14.113
(<i> hoarsely</i>): Hello.

3
00:00:14.148 --> 00:00:16.115
(<i> coughs</i>)

4
00:00:16.150 --> 00:00:18.484
(<i> hoarsely</i>): Hello.

5
00:00:18.519 --> 00:00:20.219
I love my new job!

6
00:00:20.254 --> 00:00:21.298
Honey. you're screaming.

7
00:00:21.322 --> 00:00:23.022
You bet your ass I am!

8
00:00:23.057 --> 00:00:25.424
I just had the
best first day ever.

9
00:00:25.459 --> 00:00:27.592
The kitchen? Twice
as big as Allesandro's.

10
00:00:27.628 --> 00:00:28.593
Oh. that's great.

11
00:00:28.629 --> 00:00:29.694
Yeah. and clean?

12
00:00:29.730 --> 00:00:32.631
Not just Health
Department clean.

13
00:00:32.666 --> 00:00:34.133
Monica clean!

14
00:00:34.168 --> 00:00:35.901
Awesome.

15
00:00:35.936 --> 00:00:37.802
Oh. and the people are so nice.

16
00:00:37.838 --> 00:00:39.704
There's this one
guy... Jeffrey...

17
00:00:39.740 --> 00:00:40.906
He's the maitre d'.

18
00:00:40.941 --> 00:00:43.208
Chandler. you will love him.

19
00:00:43.244 --> 00:00:46.211
He is. without a doubt. the
funniest guy I have ever met.

20
00:00:54.621 --> 00:00:59.658
♪ So no one told you life
was gonna be this way ♪

21
00:00:59.693 --> 00:01:02.094
♪ Your job's a
joke. you're broke ♪

22
00:01:02.129 --> 00:01:04.596
♪ Your love life's D.O.A. ♪

23
00:01:04.631 --> 00:01:09.468
♪ It's like you're always
stuck in second gear ♪

24
00:01:09.503 --> 00:01:11.481
♪ When it hasn't been
your day. your week ♪

25
00:01:11.505 --> 00:01:14.073
♪ Your month. or
even your year ♪

26
00:01:14.108 --> 00:01:18.143
♪ But I'll be there for you ♪

27
00:01:18.179 --> 00:01:20.579
♪ When the rain starts to pour ♪

28
00:01:20.614 --> 00:01:23.048
♪ I'll be there for you ♪

29
00:01:23.084 --> 00:01:25.584
♪ Like I've been there before ♪

30
00:01:25.619 --> 00:01:28.087
♪ I'll be there for you ♪

31
00:01:28.122 --> 00:01:34.393
♪ 'Cause you're
there for me. too. ♪

32
00:01:39.933 --> 00:01:41.133
This is nice.

33
00:01:41.168 --> 00:01:42.534
I know.

34
00:01:51.412 --> 00:01:53.223
You need both hands for that?

35
00:01:53.247 --> 00:01:54.480
Yeah. I kind of do.

36
00:01:54.515 --> 00:01:56.181
Well. how's this?

37
00:02:02.490 --> 00:02:04.089
Yeah?

38
00:02:07.461 --> 00:02:09.961
Are you sure that's
sweet enough?

39
00:02:14.335 --> 00:02:17.669
Well. look at you
two. holding hands.

40
00:02:17.704 --> 00:02:19.938
Huh? Is this getting serious?

41
00:02:19.973 --> 00:02:21.540
(<i> both stammering</i>)

42
00:02:21.575 --> 00:02:23.808
Have you not
talked about it yet?

43
00:02:25.412 --> 00:02:27.579
Am I making you uncomfortable?!

44
00:02:29.450 --> 00:02:31.883
If you were bigger.
you'd hit me. huh?

45
00:02:31.918 --> 00:02:35.687
Huh?

46
00:02:35.722 --> 00:02:37.156
I'm sorry. So sorry.

47
00:02:37.191 --> 00:02:39.158
It's obviously way too early

48
00:02:39.193 --> 00:02:42.093
for us to be having
<i>that</i> conversation.

49
00:02:42.129 --> 00:02:42.727
Is it?

50
00:02:42.763 --> 00:02:43.995
Maybe not. Is it?

51
00:02:44.031 --> 00:02:45.264
Okay.

52
00:02:45.299 --> 00:02:47.677
When I got divorced. I-I
didn't think I'd feel this way

53
00:02:47.701 --> 00:02:49.346
about someone for
a really long time.

54
00:02:49.370 --> 00:02:52.171
Mm-hmm. Then again. I didn't
think I'd meet someone like you

55
00:02:52.206 --> 00:02:54.773
and... this may be crazy soon.

56
00:02:54.808 --> 00:02:57.168
but I want you to have this.

57
00:02:58.579 --> 00:03:01.480
No. not... that's gum.

58
00:03:01.515 --> 00:03:03.815
Oh. five bucks!

59
00:03:03.850 --> 00:03:05.495
I love it when that
happens. you know?

60
00:03:05.519 --> 00:03:07.164
It's like you don't
know it's there...

61
00:03:07.188 --> 00:03:08.465
I know. Mike. Why
don't you keep digging?

62
00:03:08.489 --> 00:03:09.788
Oh. sorry.

63
00:03:13.126 --> 00:03:15.327
Oh. it's a key.

64
00:03:15.362 --> 00:03:19.064
To be honest. I think
I'd prefer the five dollars.

65
00:03:19.099 --> 00:03:21.032
It's to my apartment.

66
00:03:21.068 --> 00:03:23.268
Oh. wow. Ooh.

67
00:03:23.304 --> 00:03:25.870
Big step for Phoebe and Mike.

68
00:03:25.906 --> 00:03:27.284
Yeah. look. and I don't
want you to feel like

69
00:03:27.308 --> 00:03:28.718
you have to give me
your key just because...

70
00:03:28.742 --> 00:03:29.508
Oh. no. I want to.

71
00:03:29.543 --> 00:03:31.976
Oh. thank God.

72
00:03:32.012 --> 00:03:34.446
Yeah. Ooh. Wow.

73
00:03:34.481 --> 00:03:36.715
I was starting to think
I'd never meet someone

74
00:03:36.750 --> 00:03:39.651
that. you know. I
wanted to... do this with.

75
00:03:39.687 --> 00:03:42.221
Here you go.

76
00:03:43.591 --> 00:03:44.989
This is cool. huh?

77
00:03:45.025 --> 00:03:46.157
It really is.

78
00:03:46.193 --> 00:03:47.326
Oh. I know it.

79
00:03:47.361 --> 00:03:48.527
It is amazing.

80
00:03:48.562 --> 00:03:50.402
These little things open doors.

81
00:03:55.135 --> 00:03:58.303
So. I don't go back to
work for another four weeks.

82
00:03:58.339 --> 00:04:00.283
but we would like our
nanny to start right away

83
00:04:00.307 --> 00:04:02.252
so that Emma could
get a chance to know her.

84
00:04:02.276 --> 00:04:03.908
I think that's really smart.

85
00:04:03.944 --> 00:04:06.077
The easier we can
make the transition

86
00:04:06.113 --> 00:04:06.911
for her. the better.

87
00:04:06.947 --> 00:04:08.124
That's great. Great.

88
00:04:08.148 --> 00:04:09.526
So do you have
any questions for us?

89
00:04:09.550 --> 00:04:11.383
Not really. All right.

90
00:04:11.418 --> 00:04:12.995
Well. thank you so
much for coming.

91
00:04:13.019 --> 00:04:14.253
Thank you.

92
00:04:14.288 --> 00:04:15.599
Really nice to meet you.

93
00:04:15.623 --> 00:04:16.888
and we will call you.

94
00:04:16.923 --> 00:04:18.590
Oh. you know. wait.

95
00:04:18.626 --> 00:04:20.425
I do have one question.

96
00:04:20.461 --> 00:04:23.695
Do you guys do
random drug testing?

97
00:04:25.633 --> 00:04:26.732
Boy. we. uh...

98
00:04:26.767 --> 00:04:28.166
hadn't really thought of that.

99
00:04:28.201 --> 00:04:29.312
That's cool.

100
00:04:29.336 --> 00:04:30.347
But. if you do.

101
00:04:30.371 --> 00:04:32.904
I'm gonna need
three days' notice.

102
00:04:32.939 --> 00:04:34.973
Okeydokey!

103
00:04:35.008 --> 00:04:37.576
Wow. We're never
going to find a nanny.

104
00:04:37.611 --> 00:04:38.577
Oh. come on. Rach.

105
00:04:38.612 --> 00:04:39.612
We will. I promise.

106
00:04:39.647 --> 00:04:40.412
We have more interviews.

107
00:04:40.447 --> 00:04:41.413
Oh...

108
00:04:41.448 --> 00:04:42.847
And. worse comes to worst.

109
00:04:42.883 --> 00:04:45.784
we can always reconsider
the first one we met with.

110
00:04:45.819 --> 00:04:47.364
What. the blonde with no bra?!

111
00:04:47.388 --> 00:04:49.354
She was blond?

112
00:04:50.591 --> 00:04:52.591
(<i> knocking on door</i>)

113
00:04:52.626 --> 00:04:53.358
Just a sec!

114
00:04:53.394 --> 00:04:54.459
Okay. okay.

115
00:04:54.495 --> 00:04:56.595
This one's name is Sandy.

116
00:04:56.630 --> 00:05:00.165
Okay. She's got a degree
in Early Childhood Education.

117
00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:02.534
Uh. she worked
for her last family

118
00:05:02.569 --> 00:05:03.613
for three years.

119
00:05:03.637 --> 00:05:05.003
Okay.

120
00:05:06.707 --> 00:05:08.907
Hi. I'm Sandy.

121
00:05:13.013 --> 00:05:15.914
And she's a little mannish.

122
00:05:19.486 --> 00:05:20.719
(<i> knocking on door</i>)

123
00:05:22.055 --> 00:05:23.099
(<i> gasps</i>)

124
00:05:23.123 --> 00:05:24.956
Oh. my God! David!

125
00:05:24.991 --> 00:05:28.226
Hi. I-Is this a bad time?

126
00:05:28.261 --> 00:05:30.573
No. it's a great time. Come in!

127
00:05:30.597 --> 00:05:32.864
Wow! Hi!

128
00:05:32.899 --> 00:05:33.865
Oh. my gosh!

129
00:05:33.900 --> 00:05:35.044
What are you doing here?

130
00:05:35.068 --> 00:05:36.245
Are you back from Minsk?

131
00:05:36.269 --> 00:05:38.002
Well. just for a couple of days.

132
00:05:38.038 --> 00:05:39.204
I'm here to explain

133
00:05:39.239 --> 00:05:41.340
to the people who
gave us our grant

134
00:05:41.375 --> 00:05:44.943
why it's a positive thing that
we've spent all their money

135
00:05:44.978 --> 00:05:47.512
and. uh... uh.
accomplished. uh. nothing.

136
00:05:47.548 --> 00:05:49.359
Who cares? It got you here!

137
00:05:49.383 --> 00:05:51.182
Well. it got me to
New York. anyway.

138
00:05:51.218 --> 00:05:53.352
and then I got in
a cab at the airport.

139
00:05:53.387 --> 00:05:55.053
and the guy said. "Where to?"

140
00:05:55.088 --> 00:05:57.121
and I just... gave
him your address.

141
00:05:57.157 --> 00:05:58.824
I-I didn't even think about it.

142
00:05:58.859 --> 00:06:02.361
Wow. Where's your luggage?

143
00:06:04.130 --> 00:06:06.030
Damn it.

144
00:06:06.066 --> 00:06:09.334
All right. So I'll call
the cab company.

145
00:06:09.370 --> 00:06:10.969
W-Wait. We can call them later.

146
00:06:11.004 --> 00:06:13.605
Can I just... you just
stand there for a moment?

147
00:06:13.640 --> 00:06:15.407
(<i> laughs nervously</i>)

148
00:06:15.442 --> 00:06:19.244
Boy. Y-You... There's an
old Russian expression.

149
00:06:19.279 --> 00:06:20.712
Um. it goes...

150
00:06:20.748 --> 00:06:24.048
<i>Shtoa yazdeez vizshu: oi.</i>

151
00:06:24.084 --> 00:06:27.151
Um. roughly translated.
that means. um.

152
00:06:27.187 --> 00:06:29.821
"This thing I'm
looking at: wow."

153
00:06:31.358 --> 00:06:32.424
Thank you.

154
00:06:32.459 --> 00:06:34.659
God. no. you should
see me when...

155
00:06:34.695 --> 00:06:37.128
Oh. actually. no.
I look pretty good.

156
00:06:37.163 --> 00:06:38.430
Are... A-Are you kidding?

157
00:06:38.465 --> 00:06:41.266
You know when you don't
see someone for a long time.

158
00:06:41.301 --> 00:06:43.212
and you kind of build
them up in your head.

159
00:06:43.236 --> 00:06:46.304
and then you start thinking.
"Come on. don't be crazy.

160
00:06:46.339 --> 00:06:48.072
Nobody's that beautiful."

161
00:06:48.108 --> 00:06:49.541
But... well. you are.

162
00:06:51.879 --> 00:06:53.144
Well. so. uh...

163
00:06:53.179 --> 00:06:55.680
well. are you seeing anyone?

164
00:06:56.850 --> 00:06:59.518
No.

165
00:06:59.553 --> 00:07:02.621
I'm just... I'm the
worst person ever!

166
00:07:02.656 --> 00:07:05.290
How can I not tell David
that I'm seeing Mike?!

167
00:07:05.325 --> 00:07:07.136
Maybe he didn't
give you a chance.

168
00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:09.005
He said. "Are you
seeing someone?"

169
00:07:09.029 --> 00:07:10.662
And I said. "No."

170
00:07:10.697 --> 00:07:13.465
Oh. well. that would've
been your window.

171
00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:14.644
Yeah. I mean.

172
00:07:14.668 --> 00:07:16.435
I don't know. I was looking...

173
00:07:16.470 --> 00:07:19.504
I was looking in his eyes.
and I was just thinking

174
00:07:19.540 --> 00:07:21.684
"Oh. my God. it's
David. David's here."

175
00:07:21.708 --> 00:07:24.876
He's just. he's so irresistible.

176
00:07:24.912 --> 00:07:25.610
Really?

177
00:07:25.646 --> 00:07:26.778
The scientist guy?

178
00:07:26.814 --> 00:07:28.279
Really? Chandler?

179
00:07:34.220 --> 00:07:36.555
Continue.

180
00:07:36.590 --> 00:07:38.156
Okay. then it gets worse.

181
00:07:38.191 --> 00:07:39.302
'Cause then I told him

182
00:07:39.326 --> 00:07:41.137
that I would see
him tomorrow night.

183
00:07:41.161 --> 00:07:41.827
Phoebe!

184
00:07:41.862 --> 00:07:44.629
I know! Evil!

185
00:07:44.665 --> 00:07:46.097
And-and-and...

186
00:07:46.132 --> 00:07:48.399
I like Mike so much. you know?

187
00:07:48.435 --> 00:07:50.569
It's just going really well.

188
00:07:50.604 --> 00:07:52.571
Oh. my God!

189
00:07:52.606 --> 00:07:55.006
Wow. Isn't it ironic that
David would show up

190
00:07:55.041 --> 00:07:57.642
on the same day that you
and Mike exchange keys?

191
00:07:57.678 --> 00:08:00.044
Uh-huh.

192
00:08:00.080 --> 00:08:03.648
Yeah. you know. and given
my lifelong search for irony.

193
00:08:03.684 --> 00:08:05.717
you can imagine how happy I am.

194
00:08:07.187 --> 00:08:08.887
What are you going to do?

195
00:08:08.922 --> 00:08:12.123
I mean. I guess I just
have to... tell David

196
00:08:12.158 --> 00:08:14.726
that nothing can
happen between us.

197
00:08:14.761 --> 00:08:16.094
Unless I don't.

198
00:08:16.129 --> 00:08:21.366
You know. complicated moral
situation... no right. no wrong.

199
00:08:21.401 --> 00:08:22.479
You have to tell David.

200
00:08:22.503 --> 00:08:23.535
Okay. I knew

201
00:08:23.570 --> 00:08:25.971
I should've had this
conversation with Joey.

202
00:08:27.741 --> 00:08:30.842
Funniest guy she's ever met.

203
00:08:30.878 --> 00:08:33.277
I'm funny. right?

204
00:08:33.313 --> 00:08:36.848
What do you know? You're a door.

205
00:08:36.884 --> 00:08:39.083
You just like
"knock-knock" jokes.

206
00:08:41.989 --> 00:08:44.990
Save it for inside.

207
00:08:45.959 --> 00:08:47.358
Hey! Hey! Hey!

208
00:08:47.394 --> 00:08:49.360
So. Oklahoma's a crazy place.

209
00:08:49.396 --> 00:08:52.063
You know. they call
it the Sooner State.

210
00:08:52.098 --> 00:08:54.966
Frankly. I'd sooner
be in any other state.

211
00:08:56.803 --> 00:08:59.704
And what's with Oklahoma
having a panhandle?

212
00:08:59.740 --> 00:09:02.173
Can all states
have stuff like that?

213
00:09:02.208 --> 00:09:05.810
"Hey. yeah. I'm from the.
uh. waistband of Wyoming...

214
00:09:05.846 --> 00:09:09.347
But. when I was seven. we
headed over to the crotch."

215
00:09:09.382 --> 00:09:12.684
Was your cabin pressurized?

216
00:09:12.719 --> 00:09:13.685
(<i> chuckles</i>)

217
00:09:13.720 --> 00:09:14.986
And don't get me started

218
00:09:15.022 --> 00:09:17.000
on the way the
people from Tulsa talk.

219
00:09:17.024 --> 00:09:18.322
Okay.

220
00:09:19.860 --> 00:09:21.259
What's with the word "y'all"?

221
00:09:21.294 --> 00:09:22.493
You know. just. two words

222
00:09:22.529 --> 00:09:24.262
just pushed together?

223
00:09:24.297 --> 00:09:26.208
Are we all allowed to do that?

224
00:09:26.232 --> 00:09:28.567
Because if so. I
say why stop there?

225
00:09:28.602 --> 00:09:32.214
You know. your-your "new
poodle" could be your "noodle."

226
00:09:32.238 --> 00:09:34.839
And "fried chicken."
could be "fricken."

227
00:09:34.875 --> 00:09:38.276
Waiter! Waiter. excuse
me. "I'll have the fricken."

228
00:09:41.114 --> 00:09:42.959
See. that's. that's funny
with the fricken. right?

229
00:09:42.983 --> 00:09:45.149
No. it just reminded
me of something

230
00:09:45.185 --> 00:09:46.851
this guy did today at work.

231
00:09:46.887 --> 00:09:49.955
I-I told you about that
funny guy. Jeffrey. right?

232
00:09:49.990 --> 00:09:52.057
Yeah. he came up.

233
00:09:52.092 --> 00:09:53.992
Well. he did this bit...

234
00:09:54.027 --> 00:09:58.630
You probably had to be there.
but it was. uh. Liza Minnelli

235
00:09:58.665 --> 00:10:02.100
locked in our freezer.
eating a raw chicken.

236
00:10:02.135 --> 00:10:02.834
Oh!

237
00:10:02.869 --> 00:10:05.570
(<i> laughing</i>)

238
00:10:05.606 --> 00:10:07.739
Were you there?

239
00:10:07.774 --> 00:10:10.341
No. but it sounds like
it was fricken funny.

240
00:10:12.378 --> 00:10:14.757
I really do understand
how hard it's got to be

241
00:10:14.781 --> 00:10:16.893
to leave your child
with another person.

242
00:10:16.917 --> 00:10:20.819
I mean... it's like leaving
behind a piece of your heart.

243
00:10:20.854 --> 00:10:24.322
Sandy. that's
exactly what it is.

244
00:10:26.359 --> 00:10:28.893
Are you gay?

245
00:10:28.929 --> 00:10:30.328
Ross!

246
00:10:30.363 --> 00:10:32.241
I'm sorry. That's our Ross.

247
00:10:32.265 --> 00:10:35.033
He's just Mr. Shoots
Straight From The Hip.

248
00:10:35.068 --> 00:10:37.268
(<i> imitating gunfire</i>)

249
00:10:38.605 --> 00:10:40.905
It's okay. I get that
a lot doing what I do.

250
00:10:40.941 --> 00:10:42.040
But I am straight.

251
00:10:42.075 --> 00:10:43.407
I'm engaged. actually.

252
00:10:43.443 --> 00:10:44.776
Her name's Delia.

253
00:10:44.811 --> 00:10:46.811
Oh. that's pretty.

254
00:10:48.248 --> 00:10:50.815
So you're-you're
just... like. a...

255
00:10:50.851 --> 00:10:52.917
guy who's a nanny?

256
00:10:54.721 --> 00:10:57.989
I realize how it's a bit
unorthodox for some people.

257
00:10:58.025 --> 00:10:59.858
but I really believe

258
00:10:59.893 --> 00:11:02.861
the most satisfying thing
you can do with your life

259
00:11:02.896 --> 00:11:04.195
is take care of a child.

260
00:11:04.230 --> 00:11:06.564
Okay.

261
00:11:08.635 --> 00:11:10.101
Like. at my last job.

262
