522
00:23:42.622 --> 00:23:45.122
(<i> laughing hysterically</i>)

523
00:23:48.260 --> 00:23:49.794
Yeah.

524
00:23:52.298 --> 00:23:54.309
So those were pity laughs?

525
00:23:54.333 --> 00:23:56.467
Pity laughs?!

526
00:23:56.502 --> 00:23:58.001
Honey...

527
00:23:58.037 --> 00:23:59.737
listen.

528
00:23:59.772 --> 00:24:02.272
You have nothing to
worry about with Jeffrey.

529
00:24:02.308 --> 00:24:04.708
Oh. yeah? Is he funnier than me?

530
00:24:04.744 --> 00:24:07.210
Well. you're-you're
different funny.

531
00:24:07.246 --> 00:24:09.124
I mean. you're more sarcastic

532
00:24:09.148 --> 00:24:13.818
and-and... well. he does bits
and impressions and limericks.

533
00:24:13.853 --> 00:24:15.152
I-I do limericks.

534
00:24:15.187 --> 00:24:17.521
Uh. here once was a
man named Chandler.

535
00:24:17.557 --> 00:24:20.925
whose wife made him die inside.

536
00:24:20.960 --> 00:24:23.594
Honey. you know I
think you're hilarious.

537
00:24:23.629 --> 00:24:26.864
Come on. you know that
joke you told me last week?

538
00:24:26.899 --> 00:24:30.167
The one about Jerry Lewis
and the girl with the lazy eye.

539
00:24:30.202 --> 00:24:31.902
Slayed me.

540
00:24:31.938 --> 00:24:33.036
Hey...

541
00:24:33.072 --> 00:24:36.607
I made up that joke
and told it to you.

542
00:24:39.144 --> 00:24:41.490
Not knowing when to shut up.

543
00:24:41.514 --> 00:24:43.514
Yep. that's my thing. Yeah.

544
00:24:46.786 --> 00:24:48.085
So...

545
00:24:48.120 --> 00:24:50.955
how many guys have your key?

546
00:24:50.990 --> 00:24:52.501
No. no. no. no.
It's not... it's not...

547
00:24:52.525 --> 00:24:53.958
it's not as bad
as it looks. really.

548
00:24:53.993 --> 00:24:56.204
I was just... I was saying
good-bye to an old friend.

549
00:24:56.228 --> 00:24:58.596
Your lipstick's on his mouth.

550
00:24:58.631 --> 00:25:02.500
Oh. uh... we just. uh. happen
to wear the same shade.

551
00:25:02.535 --> 00:25:06.971
No. um... David and
I did used to go out.

552
00:25:07.006 --> 00:25:09.172
But years ago. and
he lives in Minsk.

553
00:25:09.208 --> 00:25:12.275
He's only... he's only in
town for a couple of days.

554
00:25:12.311 --> 00:25:13.978
Did you. uh... No. no.

555
00:25:14.013 --> 00:25:15.178
Kiss him?

556
00:25:15.214 --> 00:25:16.413
Oh. well. yeah.

557
00:25:17.449 --> 00:25:19.049
Yes. but look:

558
00:25:19.084 --> 00:25:21.151
She... She really likes you.

559
00:25:21.186 --> 00:25:24.354
In fact. she stopped what
was a pretty amazing kiss...

560
00:25:24.390 --> 00:25:26.189
David. David. David. David...

561
00:25:26.225 --> 00:25:27.190
No. No-no.

562
00:25:27.226 --> 00:25:28.425
He should hear this.

563
00:25:28.460 --> 00:25:29.894
I don't think you realize

564
00:25:29.929 --> 00:25:31.729
just how lucky you are. fella.

565
00:25:31.764 --> 00:25:33.463
Don't point your finger at me.

566
00:25:33.499 --> 00:25:36.133
Why? Wh-What are
you going to do about it?

567
00:25:36.168 --> 00:25:37.946
Well... I'll just show you

568
00:25:37.970 --> 00:25:40.048
what I'm going to do about it.

569
00:25:40.072 --> 00:25:42.885
You want some of
that. huh? Oh. really?

570
00:25:42.909 --> 00:25:45.442
Well. shall we
fight? I can... okay.

571
00:25:45.477 --> 00:25:48.846
Stop it! Stop it before
someone gets really hurt.

572
00:25:50.382 --> 00:25:53.584
Here. David. you should just go.

573
00:25:53.619 --> 00:25:55.786
All right.

574
00:25:55.821 --> 00:25:58.956
But... if I ever do
come back from Minsk.

575
00:25:58.991 --> 00:26:01.559
well. you'd just
better watch out.

576
00:26:01.594 --> 00:26:03.605
Well. if I ever go to Minsk.
you'd better watch out.

577
00:26:03.629 --> 00:26:04.862
Oh. you're going to Minsk?

578
00:26:04.897 --> 00:26:06.564
Well. I might.

579
00:26:06.599 --> 00:26:07.932
Really?

580
00:26:07.967 --> 00:26:10.067
Well. if you do.
come in the spring.

581
00:26:10.102 --> 00:26:11.102
It's just lovely then.

582
00:26:11.971 --> 00:26:13.604
I've heard that. actually.

583
00:26:13.639 --> 00:26:15.706
Okay. well. guys...

584
00:26:15.741 --> 00:26:18.042
Well... good-bye. Phoebe.

585
00:26:18.077 --> 00:26:19.077
Bye.

586
00:26:19.111 --> 00:26:20.355
Hey. what. are you kidding me?

587
00:26:20.379 --> 00:26:22.212
Right-o. right-o.

588
00:26:22.247 --> 00:26:24.048
Um...

589
00:26:26.485 --> 00:26:28.052
Take good care of her.

590
00:26:31.223 --> 00:26:33.190
I'm sorry. I'm so sorry.

591
00:26:33.225 --> 00:26:37.160
If you want your key
back. I totally understand.

592
00:26:37.196 --> 00:26:40.130
It's never going to
happen again. right?

593
00:26:40.165 --> 00:26:41.832
Right. Never. Never. I swear.

594
00:26:44.070 --> 00:26:46.770
Uh... oh. I just want
to say. if you. uh...

595
00:26:46.806 --> 00:26:49.773
if you do ever come to
Minsk. that's my number.

596
00:26:49.809 --> 00:26:52.876
Um... we'll. uh... we'll
party up Vladnik-style.

597
00:26:59.585 --> 00:27:04.554
(<i> recorders playing
"Hot Cross Buns"</i>)

598
00:27:08.961 --> 00:27:11.028
Yeah. all right.

599
00:27:11.063 --> 00:27:13.196
Hey. hey. Ross. check it out.

600
00:27:13.232 --> 00:27:15.532
Sandy taught me
"Hot Cross Buns."

601
00:27:15.567 --> 00:27:16.600
Really?

602
00:27:16.636 --> 00:27:18.669
Sounded like "Three Blind Mice."

603
00:27:18.704 --> 00:27:20.548
No. "Three Blind
Mice" goes like this.

604
00:27:20.572 --> 00:27:21.739
I swear to God...

605
00:27:25.244 --> 00:27:26.576
Who's up for puppets?

606
00:27:26.612 --> 00:27:28.078
Me. I'm up for puppets.

607
00:27:29.081 --> 00:27:30.247
Well. please welcome

608
00:27:30.282 --> 00:27:34.184
the Snufflebumps.

609
00:27:34.219 --> 00:27:35.753
Who wants to be Mr. Wigglemunch.

610
00:27:35.788 --> 00:27:37.721
and who's going
to be the Grumpus?

611
00:27:37.757 --> 00:27:39.300
ROSS: Okay. okay...

612
00:27:39.324 --> 00:27:43.593
how exactly is a two-month-old
supposed to appreciate puppets?

613
00:27:43.629 --> 00:27:47.097
Actually. studies have shown
that the movement and colors

614
00:27:47.133 --> 00:27:49.133
help their cerebral development.

615
00:27:49.168 --> 00:27:51.702
The whimsical
characters are just for us.

616
00:27:55.975 --> 00:27:58.842
I want to be Mr. Wigglemunch.

617
00:27:58.878 --> 00:28:01.111
Oh. my God.

618
00:28:01.147 --> 00:28:04.048
Well. I guess we know who's
going to be the Grumpus.

619
00:28:04.083 --> 00:28:06.249
(<i> laughing</i>)

620
00:28:09.388 --> 00:28:11.088
That was kind of rude.

621
00:28:11.123 --> 00:28:12.200
Oh. I'm sorry.

622
00:28:12.224 --> 00:28:16.493
Please apologize to Sandy
and the Snufflebumps for me.

623
00:28:16.528 --> 00:28:19.163
You know. he was
just doing his job.

624
00:28:19.198 --> 00:28:20.341
You know what?

625
00:28:20.365 --> 00:28:22.310
I'm... I'm sorry
I'm the only one

626
00:28:22.334 --> 00:28:25.302
who isn't in love with
"Gary Poppins" out there...

627
00:28:28.340 --> 00:28:31.408
But I-I-I just... I can't. I
can't go through with this.

628
00:28:31.443 --> 00:28:33.188
Come on. Ross. No.
Hey. you know what?

629
00:28:33.212 --> 00:28:35.278
I'm sorry. I would
never force you

630
00:28:35.314 --> 00:28:38.348
to hire someone you were
this uncomfortable with.

631
00:28:38.383 --> 00:28:40.483
(<i> sighs</i>)

632
00:28:40.519 --> 00:28:42.920
Oh. that's true.

633
00:28:42.955 --> 00:28:44.521
Thank you.

634
00:28:44.556 --> 00:28:46.289
Well. you're the one
who wants to fire him.

635
00:28:46.325 --> 00:28:47.825
so you're going
to have to go do it.

636
00:28:47.860 --> 00:28:49.860
(<i> chuckles</i>)

637
00:28:49.895 --> 00:28:52.763
So. you see. Wigglemunch.

638
00:28:52.798 --> 00:28:56.600
that's why it's
important to share.

639
00:28:58.403 --> 00:29:01.605
I am learning so much from you.

640
00:29:06.478 --> 00:29:08.345
Well. I'm off to Tulsa.

641
00:29:08.380 --> 00:29:12.850
so. if your maitre d' friend
has any funny Oklahoma jokes.

642
00:29:12.885 --> 00:29:16.854
tell him to e-mail me at
www.hahanotsomuch.com.

643
00:29:18.758 --> 00:29:20.090
Honey. you can relax.

644
00:29:20.126 --> 00:29:24.027
Last night. at work. Jeffrey
told this really sexist joke.

645
00:29:24.063 --> 00:29:26.296
After that. not so
funny anymore.

646
00:29:26.331 --> 00:29:27.375
Really? Mm-hmm.

647
00:29:27.399 --> 00:29:28.932
See? That's the thing.

648
00:29:28.968 --> 00:29:31.279
You got to keep
it smart. people.

649
00:29:31.303 --> 00:29:33.703
Okay... don't miss that flight.

650
00:29:33.739 --> 00:29:34.872
You know I love you.

651
00:29:34.907 --> 00:29:36.840
I love you. too.

652
00:29:36.876 --> 00:29:39.777
And I like you as a friend.

653
00:29:39.812 --> 00:29:40.844
Right.

654
00:29:40.880 --> 00:29:41.990
See you later.

655
00:29:42.014 --> 00:29:43.046
See ya.

656
00:29:45.317 --> 00:29:47.095
Did that guy really
make that joke?

657
00:29:47.119 --> 00:29:48.685
No. He still kills me.

658
00:29:48.720 --> 00:29:51.321
Last night. he had
me laughing so hard

659
00:29:51.356 --> 00:29:53.556
I swear a little pee came out.

660
00:30:01.733 --> 00:30:03.000
Here it goes.

661
00:30:03.035 --> 00:30:04.601
I can't watch.

662
00:30:04.636 --> 00:30:06.670
It's like firing Elmo.

663
00:30:10.642 --> 00:30:12.142
Sandy. hi.

664
00:30:12.178 --> 00:30:13.178
Hi.

665
00:30:13.212 --> 00:30:15.732
We. uh... we kind
of need to talk.

666
00:30:20.719 --> 00:30:23.159
I'm afraid it's...
it's not working out.

667
00:30:25.324 --> 00:30:27.724
Oh... Yeah. um...

668
00:30:27.759 --> 00:30:31.394
I mean. Rachel and I think
you are great with Emma.

669
00:30:31.430 --> 00:30:34.298
Um... we just feel...

670
00:30:34.333 --> 00:30:36.666
RACHEL: You.<i> You</i> feel.

671
00:30:36.702 --> 00:30:38.368
<i>I...</i>

672
00:30:38.403 --> 00:30:41.438
just feel that the...

673
00:30:41.473 --> 00:30:43.907
the chemistry isn't right.

674
00:30:43.943 --> 00:30:44.908
I'm-I'm sorry.

675
00:30:44.944 --> 00:30:46.421
We're... We're more than happy

676
00:30:46.445 --> 00:30:48.523
to give you a good
recommendation. and...

677
00:30:48.547 --> 00:30:49.813
No. no. that's okay.

678
00:30:49.849 --> 00:30:52.682
I've... had a lot of
offers from other families.

679
00:30:52.718 --> 00:30:56.720
I... just picked you guys
'cause I liked you the best.

680
00:30:56.755 --> 00:30:59.089
RACHEL: Oh. damn you. Geller.

681
00:31:02.828 --> 00:31:06.129
Anyway. uh. well. I'm glad
there's no hard feelings.

682
00:31:06.165 --> 00:31:07.231
No. none at all.

683
00:31:07.266 --> 00:31:10.567
You need to be happy
with whoever's in your home.

684
00:31:10.602 --> 00:31:13.871
Although. if you
don't mind telling me...

685
00:31:13.906 --> 00:31:14.906
Hmm?

686
00:31:14.940 --> 00:31:16.039
What was your problem?

687
00:31:16.075 --> 00:31:18.541
Maybe it's something I
can work on in the future.

688
00:31:18.577 --> 00:31:22.212
No... you know. it's-it's.
uh. nothing you did.

689
00:31:22.248 --> 00:31:24.882
It's... it's. uh...
it's my issue.

690
00:31:24.917 --> 00:31:27.951
What is it?

691
00:31:27.987 --> 00:31:30.031
(<i> chuckles uncomfortably</i>)

692
00:31:30.055 --> 00:31:31.654
Please?

693
00:31:34.960 --> 00:31:39.529
You know. I'm just not. um...
that comfortable with a guy

694
00:31:39.564 --> 00:31:41.631
who's as sensitive as you.

695
00:31:41.666 --> 00:31:42.666
(<i> sighs</i>)

696
00:31:42.701 --> 00:31:43.733
That's fair.

697
00:31:43.769 --> 00:31:46.203
Although. can I ask...

698
00:31:46.238 --> 00:31:48.471
Why do you think that is?

699
00:31:48.507 --> 00:31:50.874
Why? I-I don't know.

700
00:31:55.247 --> 00:31:58.715
Um... uh...

701
00:31:58.750 --> 00:32:01.118
maybe... maybe
because of my father?

702
00:32:01.153 --> 00:32:03.820
Mmm.

703
00:32:03.855 --> 00:32:06.390
I mean. um. you know.
when I was growing up.

704
00:32:06.425 --> 00:32:08.058
he was kind of a tough guy.

705
00:32:08.093 --> 00:32:12.930
And. as a kid. I wasn't
the athlete I am now.

706
00:32:12.965 --> 00:32:14.898
(<i> Rachel guffaws</i>)

707
00:32:14.934 --> 00:32:18.902
I play squash!

708
00:32:21.440 --> 00:32:23.473
Anyway... I. um...

709
00:32:23.508 --> 00:32:27.344
I always got the feeling he
thought<i> I</i> was too sensitive.

710
00:32:27.379 --> 00:32:29.179
That must have been hard.

711
00:32:29.214 --> 00:32:32.382
It was hard.

712
00:32:34.186 --> 00:32:37.054
No. I remember I
was in my bedroom

713
00:32:37.089 --> 00:32:39.823
playing with my dinosaurs...

714
00:32:39.858 --> 00:32:41.624
Playing and learning...

715
00:32:43.996 --> 00:32:46.396
And my father
walks in and says...

716
00:32:46.432 --> 00:32:49.566
he says. "What are you
doing with those things?

717
00:32:49.601 --> 00:32:51.168
"What's wrong with you?

718
00:32:51.203 --> 00:32:52.447
"Why aren't you...

719
00:32:52.471 --> 00:32:56.406
Why aren't you outside
playing like a... like a real boy?"

720
00:32:56.442 --> 00:32:58.141
But you are a real boy.

721
00:32:58.177 --> 00:33:00.337
(<i> crying</i>): I know I am.

722
00:33:01.646 --> 00:33:04.114
And when it's
summer and it's hot

723
00:33:04.149 --> 00:33:06.549
why can't you wear a tank top?

724
00:33:08.787 --> 00:33:11.121
It's all right.

725
00:33:11.156 --> 00:33:13.290
Listen. crying is good.

726
00:33:13.325 --> 00:33:17.060
It lets the boo-hoos out.

727
00:33:17.096 --> 00:33:19.662
Here comes some more.

728
00:33:24.069 --> 00:33:28.271
Emma. one day you're going
to grow up and be a big girl

729
00:33:28.307 --> 00:33:30.640
just like your daddy.

730
00:33:36.315 --> 00:33:38.293
And what's the one kind of boat

731
00:33:38.317 --> 00:33:39.961
that can never ever sink?

732
00:33:39.985 --> 00:33:41.151
What kind?

733
00:33:41.186 --> 00:33:43.987
A friendship.

734
00:33:46.691 --> 00:33:50.327
Wow. You blow my mind.

735
00:33:52.331 --> 00:33:53.296
Oh. I got to go.

736
00:33:53.332 --> 00:33:55.132
Oh... how much do I owe you?

737
00:33:55.167 --> 00:33:56.233
20 bucks.

738
00:33:56.268 --> 00:33:58.568
Oh. it's like the
cheapest college ever.

739
00:33:58.603 --> 00:34:00.937
Yeah. I'll see ya tomorrow.

740
00:34:00.972 --> 00:34:02.839
Okay. bye-bye. Skadandy.
